"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823437","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-24","<p>Defra officials recently met with Iceland’s Managing Director to discuss their plan to eliminate plastic in their own brands by 2023.</p><p> </p><p>Last December the Secretary of State chaired a roundtable with representatives from across the plastic sector to discuss reducing the amount of packaging produced and increasing the level of recycling.</p><p> </p><p>In November I also wrote to a number of major retailers to ask about their packaging choices for specific products.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no specific engagement with the hospitality sector.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","122913","2018-01-24T14:37:05.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823437/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823437/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-16","Licensed Premises: Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with the hospitality sector on reducing the quantity of single-use plastics in licensed premises.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","122915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823438","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>The protection of the right to freedom of religion or belief (FoRB) is a priority of Her Majesty's Government's foreign policy and will continue to be so. In their interactions with foreign governments, Foreign and Commonwealth Office ministers and officials routinely raise individual cases and highlight practices and laws that discriminate against people on the basis of their religion or belief.</p><p>The United Kingdom also actively promotes FoRB through multilateral diplomacy. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) minister with responsibility for human rights, Lord Ahmad, stressed the importance of working to defend the right to freedom of religion or belief (FoRB) when he addressed the UN Human Rights Council in September 2017.</p><p>The FCO is also supporting a number of projects to promote tolerance through the Magna Carta Fund for Human Rights and Democracy. Current projects include work to support human rights defenders in South and Central Asia.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-24T15:55:45.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823438/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823438/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps he has taken to tackle faith-based persecution overseas; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","122916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823439","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>Data is not available in the format requested. NHS Digital publishes workforce statistics, and is only available to the level of individual trusts and clinical commissioning groups.</p><p> </p><p>Nationally, the latest workforce statistics show an increase in professionally qualified clinical staff of almost 42,700 since May 2010, including over 14,900 more doctors and almost 14,200 more nurses on our wards since May 2010.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-24T14:10:03.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823439/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823439/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Great Western Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many (a) doctors, (b) nurses) and (c) other clinical staff worked at the Great Western Hospital in Swindon in (i) May 2010 and (ii) the most recent date for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","122917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823440","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>NHS Digital and NHS England’s joint ‘Hospital Accident and Emergency Activity 2016-17’ publication shows accident and emergency (A&amp;E) activity in the 2016-17 financial year.</p><p> </p><p>The publication shows the number of attendances categorised by ‘first A&amp;E treatment’, including those which were subsequently categorised as not needing hospital treatment. These are categorised as “none (consider guidance/advice option)”.The data for the 2015-16 and 2016-17 financial years is available in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of A&amp;E attendances not requiring hospital treatment</p></td><td><p>Percentage of all A&amp;E attendances</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2,164,828</p></td><td><p>10.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2,117,049</p></td><td><p>10.1%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Hospital Accident and Emergency Activity 2016-17</p><p> </p><p>The ‘Hospital Accident and Emergency Activity 2016-17’ publication is available via the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB30112" target="_blank">http://digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB30112</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-24T12:30:43.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823440/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823440/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent estimate he has made of the number of people presenting at A&E who do not require hospital treatment.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","122918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823441","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>NHS Improvement report that in December 2017 (2017-18 Quarter 3), 134 out of 136 (98.5%) trusts with a Type 1 accident and emergency department have primary care streaming in place. This is an improvement from the November 2017 (Quarter 2) position of 91% (125/136) and the July 2017 (Quarter 1) position of 30% (41/136).</p><p> </p><p>There are two trusts still to implement primary care streaming (Isle of Wight NHS Trust and Great Western Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust). NHS Improvement are working with these trusts on implementation.</p><p> </p><p>Birmingham Women and Children’s NHS Foundation Trust and Dorset County Hospital NHS Foundation Trust are exempt based on local requirements.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-24T17:48:52.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823441/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823441/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many hospitals have a GP co-located on site to provide triage services for patients.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","122919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823442","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>Government continually reviews the portfolio of strategic suppliers and is in the process of identifying new strategic suppliers to add to the list. This update will be announced in due course.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-01-22T16:23:24.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823442/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823442/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the oral evidence given by John Manzoni, Permanent Secretary to the Cabinet Office, to the Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Committee on 15 January 2018, what the evidential basis was for his statement that there were 35 strategic suppliers when only 29 are listed in the document entitled Crown Representatives and Strategic Suppliers (September 2017).","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","122920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823444","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Advisory Council publishes its own annual report which is laid before Parliament. Since the transition from the 30 year rule to 20 year rule began in 2013, the Advisory Council has collated and published annual figures on closures and retention, and the outcomes of these applications. The Council also reports on the work of its Freedom of Information Panels. The information can be found in its annual reports, available at <a href="http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/about/our-role/plans-policies-performance-and-projects/our-performance/" target="_blank">http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/about/our-role/plans-policies-performance-and-projects/our-performance/</a></p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","122921","2018-01-24T16:30:38.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823444/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823444/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-16","Advisory Council on National Records and Archives: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many appeals the Advisory Council on National Records and Archives has (a) heard, (b) ruled in favour of and (c) ruled against in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","122922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823445","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>Flu vaccines for people aged 18 years and older are procured directly from manufacturers and suppliers by providers. The procurement and distribution of flu vaccines for the children’s aspect of the national flu programme is managed by Public Health England.</p><p> </p><p>Flu vaccine remains available to order from manufacturers and suppliers across England for both the adult and the children’s aspects of the national flu immunisation programme.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are continuously monitoring the flu vaccine supply landscape to enable timely and appropriate action to be taken in the event that demand begins to outweigh the amount of flu vaccine that is currently available to patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","122924","2018-01-24T11:59:58.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823445/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823445/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the availability of stocks of flu vaccines in (a) York and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","122923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823446","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>Flu vaccines for people aged 18 years and older are procured directly from manufacturers and suppliers by providers. The procurement and distribution of flu vaccines for the children’s aspect of the national flu programme is managed by Public Health England.</p><p> </p><p>Flu vaccine remains available to order from manufacturers and suppliers across England for both the adult and the children’s aspects of the national flu immunisation programme.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are continuously monitoring the flu vaccine supply landscape to enable timely and appropriate action to be taken in the event that demand begins to outweigh the amount of flu vaccine that is currently available to patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","122923","2018-01-24T11:59:58.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823446/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823446/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans his Department has to increase the supply of flu vaccines to areas in the event that there are shortfalls of such vaccines during Winter 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","122924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823447","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Government has no plans to introduce a fixed time limit on immigration detention as this would only encourage detainees to refuse to cooperate with immigration and asylum processes until they reached the point at which they had to be released from detention and thus avoid their enforced removal from the UK. Published Home Office policy is clear, however, that detention is only used for the shortest period necessary, during which time any health and welfare needs detained persons may have are met through the provision of appropriate services</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/offender-management" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/offender-management</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes","122928","2018-01-22T17:42:15.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823447/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823447/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had on introducing a clear limit on the length of time people can be held in immigration removal centres; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","122925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823448","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>Detention is an important part of a firm but fair immigration system, helping to ensure that those with no right to remain in the UK are returned to their home country if they will not leave voluntarily. There is an underpinning presumption in immigration policy that a person will not be detained. Immigration detention is used sparingly and for the shortest period necessary.</p><p>When a vulnerable individual is considered for immigration detention, that consideration takes place in line with the adults at risk in immigration detention policy. The policy came into force in September 2016 and was part of the Government’s response to Stephen Shaw’s review of the welfare of vulnerable people in immigration detention. Victims of torture and individuals suffering from a mental health condition are amongst the groups of individuals who are protected by this policy.</p><p>Each case is decided on its own merits, on the basis of available evidence. Vulnerable individuals are detained only when immigration control factors – removability, public protection and compliance with immigration law – in their particular case outweigh the evidence of their vulnerability.</p><p>All detention decisions are subject to review by the Home Office Detention Gatekeeper, which is an internally independent function.</p><p>It is not possible for an individual to be detained having been assessed as unsuitable for detention by the Detention Gatekeeper, whether it be on grounds of mental health, as a victims of torture or a victim of modern slavery.</p><p>The Government considers that the adults at risk policy is an effective safeguard against the inappropriate detention of vulnerable people.</p><p>Once detained the Home Office has additional safeguards in place to ensure that vulnerable people do not remain in detention longer than is necessary or appropriate. Since February 2017 Case Progression Panels have been internally reviewing cases every three months to ensure case progression towards return.</p><p>From the 15 January 2018, the Secretary of State has a duty to refer individuals to the independent Immigration and Asylum Tribunal for consideration of bail four months from the point of detention of the last Tribunal consideration of bail and every four months thereafter. This duty does not extend to individuals detained for deportation or on national security grounds.</p><p>The follow up to the independent review by Stephen Shaw CBE into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons started on 4 September 2017. As part of this stocktake Mr Shaw will be assessing the implementation of all of his earlier review recommendations.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-22T17:43:57.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823448/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823448/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of safeguards to ensure that (a) vulnerable people diagnosed with a mental health condition and (b) victims of torture are not held in immigration removal centres.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","122926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823450","Home Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>Information on the number of minors entering and in detention in the UK from 2014, is available in tables dt_02_q and dt_13_q of the detention tables in the latest release of ‘Immigration Statistics, July to September 2017’, available from the Home Office website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662536/detention-jul-sep-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662536/detention-jul-sep-2017-tables.ods</a>. Figures for Q4 2017 will be released on 22 February 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-23T07:31:57.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823450/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823450/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people aged 18 and under were held in immigration detention centres in each year from 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","122927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823451","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Government has no plans to introduce a fixed time limit on immigration detention as this would only encourage detainees to refuse to cooperate with immigration and asylum processes until they reached the point at which they had to be released from detention and thus avoid their enforced removal from the UK. Published Home Office policy is clear, however, that detention is only used for the shortest period necessary, during which time any health and welfare needs detained persons may have are met through the provision of appropriate services</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/offender-management" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/offender-management</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes","122925","2018-01-22T17:42:15.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823451/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823451/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of indefinite detention in an immigration detention removal centre on the health and wellbeing of such detainees.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","122928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823452","Home Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>The follow up to the independent review by Stephen Shaw CBE into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons started on 4 September 2017. As part of this stocktake Mr Shaw will be assessing the implementation of all of his earlier review recommendations.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-23T07:33:04.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823452/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823452/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Welfare in Detention of Vulnerable Persons Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made on implementing the recommendations from the Shaw Review into the Welfare in Detention of Vulnerable Persons, published in January 2016.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","122929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823454","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-19","<p>HM Treasury regularly engages with a diverse group of people about the insurance sector.</p><p> </p><p>The government is focussed on ensuring that the insurance industry functions well for everyone. Insurance firms are required to treat customers fairly under the rules of the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).</p><p> </p><p>New FCA rules on consumer insurance policy renewals, introduced in April 2017, will encourage consumers to shop around instead of renewing their policy automatically. The FCA will monitor the effect of the rules and the government will ask the FCA to consider further intervention if necessary.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-01-19T12:46:04.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823454/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823454/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-16","House Insurance: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received on the loyalty penalty faced by consumers who do not switch home insurance providers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","122930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823455","Department for Education","false","2018-01-19","<p>Following the announcement on 15 January 2018, regarding the collapse of Carillion, the Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA) have made contingency plans and identified The Construction Industry Training Board (CITB) as the best placed alternative provider. CITB are on the ESFA’s register of approved apprenticeship training providers and have delivered the frameworks/standards that current Carillion apprentices are studying. We understand that the CITB centres are situated within reasonable travelling distance for the apprentices and they have the capacity to take on the transferring apprentices and study programme learners.</p><p> </p><p>The ESFA contacted all affected apprentices on 15 January to notify them of the situation and the ‘Study Programme Learners’ will also be notified by letter on the 17 January. Affected learners have been provided with the details of a dedicated mailbox, <a href="mailto:Carillion.Construction@education.gov.uk" target="_blank">Carillion.Construction@education.gov.uk</a><strong>,</strong> where they can raise any issues or concerns.</p><p> </p><p>The CITB are already working with their established network of college partners to support all the apprentices and other learners to complete their programmes. They are also utilising their existing employer contacts in the sector and the grant incentives they have available to find alternative employers for the apprentices to complete their frameworks or standards. Additionally, CITB are making contact with Carillion supply chain companies and have reported that numerous employers have responded with offers of support.</p><p> </p><p>CITB have scheduled a series of workshops for learners, which will take place in the regions of the 11 Carillion Training Centres, providing advice on the next steps. The timings and locations of these events will be communicated by telephone and on their website. Carillion will also encourage their learners to attend.</p><p> </p><p>Carillion have sent out communication to their learners, alerting them to the situation and reassuring them that support is in place.</p><p> </p><p>The ESFA are meeting with CITB daily to monitor progress and resolve any issues.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-01-19T13:43:08.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823455/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823455/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to support apprentices affected by the collapse of Carillion plc.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823456","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Foreign Secretary met Foreign Minister Çavuşoğlu, on 16 January. The Foreign Secretary and I have regular conversations with our Turkish counterparts in which we discuss the full range of our shared security, prosperity and consular priorities including the rule of law and human rights situation in Turkey, counter terrorism and regional security, and bilateral trade.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-01-19T14:45:10.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823456/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823456/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","Turkey: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he last met with his Turkish counterpart; and what issues were discussed at that meeting.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","122932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823457","Department for Education","false","2018-01-22","<p>Local authorities and academy trusts are responsible for their contracts. We have, however, worked with local authorities and academy trusts to make sure they have robust contingency plans in place and that these have been actioned, where required. Information available to the department indicates that the number of local authority and academy trust schools, covered by catering, facilities management or other service contracts with Carillion is relatively low.</p><p> </p><p>Our priority is to ensure schools can continue to operate as usual. Government is supporting the Official Receiver, so that services to schools and other public services can continue to be delivered.</p><p> </p><p>We are continuing to monitor the situation and will work with schools and providers to help minimise any disruption for pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","122936","2018-01-22T15:26:52.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823457/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823457/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Academies: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of academies in (a) the West Midlands and (b) Coventry have contracts with Carillion plc for catering services.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","122933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823458","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-22","<p>Network Rail has advised the Department for Transport that it does not hold any contracts with Carillion for rail ‎improvements in the West Midlands or Coventry.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-22T14:13:13.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823458/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823458/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823458/answer/previousversion/35246","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what rail improvement contracts Carillion plc holds in (a) the West Midlands and (b) Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","122934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823459","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Government has collected £32m in Employment Tribunal fees since 2013. We immediately stopped charging fees following the Supreme Court’s judgment in July 2017, and the refund scheme was launched on 15 November 2017.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-25T18:44:27.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823459/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823459/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-16","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much money has been spent on employment tribunal fees since their introduction in 2013.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","122935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823460","Department for Education","false","2018-01-22","<p>Local authorities and academy trusts are responsible for their contracts. We have, however, worked with local authorities and academy trusts to make sure they have robust contingency plans in place and that these have been actioned, where required. Information available to the department indicates that the number of local authority and academy trust schools, covered by catering, facilities management or other service contracts with Carillion is relatively low.</p><p> </p><p>Our priority is to ensure schools can continue to operate as usual. Government is supporting the Official Receiver, so that services to schools and other public services can continue to be delivered.</p><p> </p><p>We are continuing to monitor the situation and will work with schools and providers to help minimise any disruption for pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","122933","2018-01-22T15:26:52.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823460/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823460/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Schools: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of local authority maintained schools receive school maintenance services from Carillion plc in (a) the West Midlands and (b) Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","122936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823462","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>The number of people who paid Employment Tribunal fees is not recorded centrally. However, statistics on the instances in which a fee is charged (for single and multiple claims) are published in the ‘Tribunals and Gender Recognitions Statistics Quarterly,’ available at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The full refund scheme was rolled out on 15 November. Anyone who paid a fee can now apply for a refund. Provisional Management information on the number of refunds paid, and their value, was published on the 18 January 2018 on the gov.uk website, which showed as at 18 December we have made 2,151 refunds worth £1.8 million.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-25T18:45:27.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823462/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823462/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-16","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people (a) paid employment tribunal fees and (b) claimed a refund for employment tribunal fees since the introduction of those fees in 2013.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","122937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823463","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>The full Employment Tribunals Refund scheme was launched on 15 November 2017. Provisional Management information on the number of refunds paid, and their value, was published on the 18 January 2018 on the gov.uk website, which showed as at 18 December we have made 2,151 refunds worth £1.8 million.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to keep the volume of applications we receive under review, and are considering whether any further measures may be needed to raise awareness of the scheme, so that everyone entitled to a refund is aware of the scheme and how to apply.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-25T18:46:08.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823463/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823463/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-16","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to encourage people to reclaim their tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","122938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823464","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>The information available relating to visitor entry clearance visas for Turkish nationals is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662518/entry-visas1-jul-sep-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662518/entry-visas1-jul-sep-2017-tables.ods </a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-22T17:40:37.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823464/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823464/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Visas: Turkey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Turkish nationals have been refused six month visitor visas in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","122939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823465","Department for Education","false","2018-01-24","<p>We do not hold data relating to the number of children eligible for 30 hours who are disabled.</p><p> </p><p>We will collect data about the number of children taking up 30 hours free childcare in the January 2018 Early Years and Schools Census. This will be published in the ‘Education provision: children under 5 years of age’ statistical first release in summer 2018. This will include data about the number of children with special educational needs or a disability taking up government-funded hours.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-24T14:16:42.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823465/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823465/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of children aged three and four who are entitled to free childcare for 30 hours a week are disabled.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","122940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823467","Department for Education","false","2018-01-19","<p>We do not currently hold data about the number of free hours that are being used by children that are eligible for 30 hours or the reasons why a child may not be accessing their full entitlement.</p><p> </p><p>We will collect data about the number of children taking up 30 hours free childcare in January 2018 Early Years and Schools Census. This will be published in the ‘Education provision: children under 5 years of age’ statistical first release in summer 2018. This will include data about the number of children with special educational needs or a disability taking up government-funded hours.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-19T14:48:53.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823467/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823467/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he has made an estimate of how many children are not currently accessing their full 30 hours of free childcare because their specialist needs are not being accommodated.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","122941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823468","Department for Education","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Childcare Act 2006 and Childcare Act 2016 make clear that if children meet the eligibility requirements for the free entitlements, the local authority must secure a place for them. The Equality Act 2010 requires that local authorities and all early years’ providers must make reasonable adjustments for disabled children.</p><p>Local authorities can use the high needs element of their Dedicated Schools Grant to support settings to provide childcare to disabled children. In addition, we introduced, in April 2017, a national Disability Access Fund, worth to £615 per child per year, to support disabled children to access the free entitlements.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-19T14:46:31.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823468/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823468/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he plans to take to ensure that disabled three and four year olds who require one-to-one care can still access the thirty hours of free childcare to which they are entitled.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","122942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823469","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Member to my previous answer (121269).</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-23T13:48:16.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823469/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823469/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823469/answer/previousversion/35489","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 16 January 2018 to Question 121269, how much of the £1.2 billion of funding for the Starter Home Land Fund has been spent to date.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","122943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823470","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-19","<p>The table below shows the proportion of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) decisions that went to appeal, by year of decision in the Parliamentary Constituency of St Helens South and Whiston.</p><p> </p><p><em>Proportion of PIP decisions that went to appeal, by financial year of decision in the Parliamentary Constituency of </em><em>St Helens South and Whiston</em><em>.</em></p><p><em> </em></p><p><em> </em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year of initial PIP decision</p></td><td><p>Proportion of PIP decisions that went to appeal</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr'17 to Oct'17</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em> </em></p><p>Latest available data to October 2017</p><p> </p><p>The information for Employment Support Allowance (ESA) is not readily available and can only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-19T11:24:30.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823470/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823470/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Social Security Benefits: St Helens South and Whiston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of claims for (a) employment support allowance and (b) personal independence payments went to appeal in St Helens South and Whiston constituency in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","122944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823471","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-19","<p>RAF fire personnel based at Kinloss began providing cover to the civilian manned fire station at RAF Lossiemouth from August 2014. Therefore, data is only available from this period.</p><p> </p><p>The number of occasions RAF personnel based at Kinloss have supported the civilian manned fire station at RAF Lossiemouth is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2014 – 129</p><p>2015 – 384</p><p>2016 – 419</p><p>2017 – 514</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-19T14:20:08.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823471/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823471/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-16","RAF Lossiemouth: Fire and Rescue Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on how many occasions RAF fire personnel based at Kinloss have been used to support the civilian manned fire station at RAF Lossiemouth in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","122945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823472","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department does not discuss car parking charges with local organisations. The provision of parking spaces and the level of any charges that are made to use them are matters for individual National Health Service organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Details of charges, concessions and additional charges should be well publicised including at car park entrances, wherever payment is made and inside the hospital. They should also be included on the hospital website and on patient letters and forms, where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published guidelines (the car parking principles) for NHS organisations that they are expected to follow.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","122947 ; 122950 ; 122952","2018-01-24T12:36:03.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823472/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823472/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to his Department's guidance on NHS patient, visitor and staff car parking principles, last updated on 29 October 2015, whether he has had discussions with local authorities in Essex on what constitutes a reasonable charge to park at a hospital in Essex for (a) one hour, (b) four hours, (c) one day and (d) one week.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","122946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823473","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department does not discuss car parking charges with local organisations. The provision of parking spaces and the level of any charges that are made to use them are matters for individual National Health Service organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Details of charges, concessions and additional charges should be well publicised including at car park entrances, wherever payment is made and inside the hospital. They should also be included on the hospital website and on patient letters and forms, where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published guidelines (the car parking principles) for NHS organisations that they are expected to follow.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","122946 ; 122950 ; 122952","2018-01-24T12:36:03.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823473/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823473/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to his Department's guidance on NHS patient, visitor and staff car parking principles, last updated on 29 October 2015, whether he has had discussions with local authorities in London on what constitutes a reasonable charge to park at a hospital in London for (a) one hour, (b) four hours, (c) one day and (d) one week.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","122947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823474","Department for Education","false","2018-01-19","<p>No schools will lose funding in the current academic year for those Year 9 pupils who have made an early transfer to Warrington University Technical College (UTC). The department is aware that concerns have been raised about the UTC’s actions and is discussing them with the UTC, the local authority and representatives from local schools.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-01-19T18:22:59.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823474/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823474/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Schools: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he plans to take steps to compensate schools in Warrington for financial detriment experienced as a result of the unauthorised recruitment of pupils to an accelerated Key Stage 4 programme by Warrington UTC.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","122948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823476","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-19","<p>As Civil Servants, Defence Fire and Rescue Service (DFRS) personnel are members of the Civil Service Pension Schemes. The Department has worked closely with Cabinet Office and HM Treasury to offer a reduced Effective Pension Age for DFRS personnel, recognising the physical demands placed upon them, and is currently in consultation with the relevant Trade Unions to finalise this offer.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-19T14:19:35.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823476/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823476/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-16","Defence Fire and Rescue Service: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he plans to review the adequacy of pensions arrangements for his Department's fire-fighters.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","122949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823477","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department does not discuss car parking charges with local organisations. The provision of parking spaces and the level of any charges that are made to use them are matters for individual National Health Service organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Details of charges, concessions and additional charges should be well publicised including at car park entrances, wherever payment is made and inside the hospital. They should also be included on the hospital website and on patient letters and forms, where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published guidelines (the car parking principles) for NHS organisations that they are expected to follow.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","122946 ; 122947 ; 122952","2018-01-24T12:36:03.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823477/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823477/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to his Department's guidance on NHS patient, visitor and staff car parking principles, last updated on 29 October 2015, whether he has had discussions with local authorities in Harlow on what constitutes a reasonable charge to park at a hospital in Harlow for (a) one hour, (b) four hours, (c) one day and (d) one week.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","122950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823478","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-19","<p>Funding for 2018/2019 to promote Access to Work has not been finalised. For our marketing approach, I refer the Hon Member to PQ 106839.</p><p>Last year saw an 8% rise in number of people who had an Access to Work award approved.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-19T14:01:14.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823478/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823478/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Access to Work Programme: Publicity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2017 to Question 106843, how much her Department plans to spend on promoting the Access to Work scheme in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","122951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823479","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department does not discuss car parking charges with local organisations. The provision of parking spaces and the level of any charges that are made to use them are matters for individual National Health Service organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Details of charges, concessions and additional charges should be well publicised including at car park entrances, wherever payment is made and inside the hospital. They should also be included on the hospital website and on patient letters and forms, where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published guidelines (the car parking principles) for NHS organisations that they are expected to follow.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","122946 ; 122947 ; 122950","2018-01-24T12:36:03.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823479/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823479/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to his Department's guidance on NHS patient, visitor and staff car parking principles, last updated on 29 October 2015, whether he has had discussions with local authorities in the East of England on what constitutes a reasonable charge to park at a hospital in that region for (a) one hour, (b) four hours, (c) one day and (d) one week.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","122952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823480","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>Access to Work is promoted to a range of business leaders through the Disability Confident campaign. As part of the ongoing Access to Work campaign partnership managers will be engaging with local contacts to promote the support available.</p><p> </p><p>We also promote the scheme through engagement with partners and stakeholders such as Remploy, as well as through other government departments and public sector bodies. We may also use some elements of paid for marketing where appropriate, although our spending plans have not yet been finalised.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-24T17:50:45.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823480/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823480/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Access to Work Programme: Publicity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to better promote the Access to Work scheme.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","122953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823481","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>The safety of residents should be local authorities' number one priority.</p><p>36 local authorities have been in touch with the Department in regards to fire safety funding. 10 of these have been asked to provide further information about the specifics of the building safety work required, and 4 of these 10 have returned this information.</p><p>We are in constructive discussions with these local authorities in regards to what financial flexibilities we can offer them in order for them to complete essential fire safety work to make their specific buildings safe. This might include increasing Housing Revenue Account borrowing, but we will also consider other flexibilities, including transfers from the general fund.</p><p>We have not yet completed this process for any local authority but the fact that discussions are on-going does not stop local authorities from getting on with essential fire safety works.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-23T13:43:50.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823481/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823481/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823481/answer/previousversion/35490","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities have requested the Government for assistance as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire; how many of those authorities have requested financial assistance in the form of increased housing revenue account borrowing capacity; and how many such authorities requesting such assistance have had their requests granted (a) in part or (b) fully.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","122954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823482","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>There have been no deaths over the last five years of people being removed under escort on a flight from the UK.</p><p>Published Immigration Enforcement transparency data shows that there were 7,678 attempted escorted removals in 2015, 8,175 in 2016 and 3,873 in 2017 up to 30 June (quarter 2). It can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#immigration-enforcement" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#immigration-enforcement</a>.</p><p>Information on the timing of any injury (whether immediately before boarding or on-board) and the type of escorted removal (whether scheduled or Home Office charter flight) is not readily available from central records and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost through a manual search of individual case files.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes",,"2018-01-22T15:43:25.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823482/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823482/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people assigned for deportation have (a) sustained injuries or (b) died (i) immediately before boarding or (ii) onboard deportation flights leaving the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","122955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823483","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>​The Taipei Representative Office in London has contacted the UK Government to express its concern regarding the announcement by the Chinese authorities to activate air routes M503, W121, W122 and W123.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-24T15:46:42.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823483/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823483/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","China: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has received from the Taipei Representative Office on the announcement by the Civil Aviation Administration of China that it plans to will activate air routes M503, W121, W122 and W123 that are close to Taiwan’s Flight Information Region.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","122956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823484","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>​We understand that the opening of the four new air routes in the Taiwan Strait on 4 January is a cause of concern for the authorities in Taiwan.</p><p>Her Majesty's Government is assessing whether the introduction of these new northbound flights in the Straits will have any impact on aviation safety in the region.</p><p>In line with our longstanding position, we encourage China and Taiwan to engage in peaceful dialogue to resolve this issue.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-24T15:50:16.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823484/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823484/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","China: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the announcement of 4 January 2019 by the Civil Aviation Administration of China that it will activate four air routes M503, W121, W122 and W123 close to Taiwan’s Flight Information Region, what assessment he has made of the effect of that policy on relations between Taiwan and China.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","122957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823485","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>As one of its founding signatories, the UK is a strong supporter of the Convention on the Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling, Production and Transfer of Anti-Personnel Mines and on their Destruction. We regularly encourage states who have not signed the Convention to do so, as promoting universal adherence to the Convention is a top priority in the area of human security and disarmament.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-24T16:14:03.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823485/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823485/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","Egypt: Land Mines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to encourage the Egyptian Government to accede to the Convention on the Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling, Production and Transfer of Anti-Personnel Mines and on their Destruction.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","122958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823487","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-22","<p>This Government is committed to improving perinatal mental health services for women during pregnancy and in the first postnatal year, so that women are able to access the right care at the right time and close to home.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is investing £365 million from 2015/16 to 2020/21 in perinatal mental health services, and NHS England is leading a transformation programme to ensure that by 2020/21 at least 30,000 more women each year are able to access evidence-based specialist mental health care during the perinatal period. This includes access to psychological therapies and specialist community or inpatient care.</p><p> </p><p>A key element of the programme is to increase awareness and skills across the workforce, supporting better identification of perinatal mental illness, early intervention and consequently improved recovery rates. In addition, there are over 570 perinatal mental health visitor champions. Their role is to support health visitors with the identification and management of anxiety, mild to moderate depression and other perinatal mental disorders, and knowing when to refer on.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-22T11:45:15.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823487/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823487/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Mental Health Services: Mothers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that new mothers' mental health problems are identified as early as possible.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","122959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823488","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office does not hold current estimates on the number of World War Two era mines that remain un-disposed of in the Tobruk and El-Alamein regions. The package of UK support to Libya announced in August 2017 includes £1 million this year to fund demining training and education across the country and increase the capacity of Libyan authorities to deal with explosive hazards. The UK has supported demining in Egypt since 2006 through multilateral funding along with other donors including Germany, Japan, New Zealand and the US. The projects have funded clearance of 130,446 acres of land around El Alamein, provision of artificial limbs for 479 land mine victims, and three mine risk education campaigns benefiting 160,000 individuals. The UK has previously provided maps of minefield locations to the Egyptian authorities.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-24T16:16:36.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823488/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823488/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","North Africa: Land Mines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department holds on the number of World War Two era mines that remain un-disposed of in the Tobruk and El-Alamein regions.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","122960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823489","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-23","<p>The package of UK support to Libya announced in August 2017 includes £1 million this year to fund demining training and education across the country and increase the capacity of Libyan authorities to deal with explosive hazards. The UK has supported demining in Egypt since 2006 through multilateral funding along with other donors including Germany, Japan, New Zealand and the US. The projects have funded clearance of 130,446 acres of land around El Alamein, provision of artificial limbs for 479 land mine victims, and three mine risk education campaigns benefiting 160,000 individuals. The UK has previously provided maps of minefield locations to the Egyptian authorities. The UK currently has no programmes specifically targeting WWII ordnance in the Tobruk or El-Alamein regions.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-23T17:38:13.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823489/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823489/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-16","North Africa: Land Mines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is taking steps to assist with the mapping and disposal of World War Two-era mines in the Tobruk and El-Alamein regions; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","122961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823490","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>Information about the number of disposable cups used each year is not held centrally.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","123153","2018-03-21T14:33:13.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823490/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823490/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Cabinet Office: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate has been made of the number of hot drink cups that are (a) used each year and (b) sent for recycling by his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823491","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Department was created in July 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s catering supplier, Baxter Storey, purchased the following disposable cups for use in the staff restaurants and coffee shops:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>No. of cups</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>60,832</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>48,912</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department makes provision for recycling and has specially marked recycling bins throughout the Department.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-23T16:41:02.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823491/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823491/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate has been made of the number of hot drink cups that are (a) used each year and (b) sent for recycling by his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823492","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-23","<p>DCMS do not purchase any hot drinks cups. DCMS is based at 100 Parliament Street and as such staff use facilities provided by HM Treasury.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-23T11:02:50.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823492/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823492/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-16","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Beverage Containers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate has been made of the number of hot drink cups that are (a) used each year and (b) sent for recycling by his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823493","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-19","<p>As the Minister for Rail, such meetings are my responsibility and I am always happy to meet with my honourable colleague; my office will be in touch to arrange a suitable date.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-19T08:46:01.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823493/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823493/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Railways: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to his oral contribution of 29 November 2017, Official Report, column.350, when he plans to meet the hon. Member for Leeds West to discuss the frequency of train services at Kirkstall Forge station in Leeds.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","122965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823494","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-19","<p>The new Board of Trade is led by the President of the Board of Trade. The Secretaries of State for the Territorial Offices and other Department for International Trade Ministers have a standing invitation to attend the meetings. The work of the Board of Trade is supported by a group of Advisers. A full list of the Advisers to the Board of Trade can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/news/international-trade-secretary-dr-liam-fox-convenes-a-new-board-of-trade-to-ensure-the-benefits-of-free-trade-are-spread-throughout-the-uk</p><p>The next meeting of the Board of Trade will take place in the first quarter of 2018.</p><p>The purpose of the Board of Trade is to support businesses and spread the benefits of trade and investment to all parts of the United Kingdom by maximising the positive impact of the support that HMG provides to English regions, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","122967 ; 122969","2018-01-19T11:59:53.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823494/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823494/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-16","Board of Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, who the full members of the Board of Trade are.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122966"
