"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823496","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence is clear that it does not tolerate any form of abuse. We take all allegations very seriously and have mechanisms in place to ensure they are handled appropriately.</p><p>The avenues of redress open to former personnel who allege physical or verbal abuse from other members of the Armed Forces will depend on the circumstances of the case; including when and where the abuse took place and whether it amounts to a criminal assault.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-01-24T16:06:24.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823496/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823496/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-16","Veterans: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that adequate measures for redress are in place for ex-servicemen and women who claim to have been the victims of physical and verbal abuse from other members of the armed forces during their service.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","122968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823498","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-19","<p>The new Board of Trade is led by the President of the Board of Trade. The Secretaries of State for the Territorial Offices and other Department for International Trade Ministers have a standing invitation to attend the meetings. The work of the Board of Trade is supported by a group of Advisers. A full list of the Advisers to the Board of Trade can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/news/international-trade-secretary-dr-liam-fox-convenes-a-new-board-of-trade-to-ensure-the-benefits-of-free-trade-are-spread-throughout-the-uk</p><p>The next meeting of the Board of Trade will take place in the first quarter of 2018.</p><p>The purpose of the Board of Trade is to support businesses and spread the benefits of trade and investment to all parts of the United Kingdom by maximising the positive impact of the support that HMG provides to English regions, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","122966 ; 122967","2018-01-19T11:59:53.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823498/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823498/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-16","Board of Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the agenda is for the next meeting of the Board of Trade.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823499","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-24","<p>We are committed to meeting existing EU targets on recycling of packaging and household waste for 2020 and have no plans to introduce further targets for that date.</p><p> </p><p>The resources and waste strategy, to be published later this year, will set out future targets and milestones on this area.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-24T13:15:06.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823499/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823499/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-16","Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will set targets for recycling rates for the periods (a) by 2020 and (b) by 2030.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","122970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823500","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-19","<p>The PIP assessment is not a medical assessment requiring the assessor to diagnose a condition or its severity and recommend treatment options. The focus is on ensuring that Health Professionals are experts in disability analysis, considering the effects of health conditions and impairments on an individual’s daily life.</p><p> </p><p>Both Independent Assessment Services and Capita are required to ensure that the Health Professionals carrying out assessments have knowledge of the clinical aspects and likely functional effects of a wide range of health conditions and impairments.</p><p> </p><p>All Health Professionals undertaking PIP assessments must be registered practitioners who have also met requirements around training and competence. They must be an occupational therapist, level 1 nurse, physiotherapist, paramedic or doctor. They must also be fully registered and have at least 2 years post full-registration experience. Prior to carrying out an assessment they refresh their knowledge of any condition which they are not fully familiar with. All Health Professionals are subject to on-going quality audit to ensure they continue to deliver high quality assessments.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-19T11:32:51.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823500/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823500/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Personal Independence Payment: Charcot Marie Tooth Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether disability assessors for personal independence payments receive training that includes information relating to Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823501","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-22","<p>The latest official DWP survey shows that overall satisfaction for Personal Independent Payment stands at 76%</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The information is available on GOV.UK:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/583754/dwp-claimant-service-and-experience-survey-2015-2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/583754/dwp-claimant-service-and-experience-survey-2015-2016.pdf</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-22T14:27:19.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823501/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823501/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Personal Independence Payment: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department holds data on customer satisfaction for the disability assessment service for personal independence payments; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823502","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-19","<p>Highways England’s main contractor delivering its improvement scheme at Switch Island is Balfour Beatty Mott MacDonald. Work on the project is scheduled to commence on 5 February 2018 and last for twelve months. Carillion was not involved in the project, and Highways England’s capacity to complete the work will not be affected.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-19T08:58:30.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823502/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823502/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, who the main contractor on the A59 switch island planned works is; when that work is due to start; and whether the capacity to complete the work will be affected by the liquidation of Carillion.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","122973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823503","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-22","<p>The number of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) cleared claims that were disallowed can be found via Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>The relevant data can be found in Table 2 – PIP Clearances by Clearance Type.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The number of Mandatory Reconsiderations (MRs) can be found in the DWP published statistics “Personal Independence Payment: April 2013 to October 2017”. The relevant data is in “Table 7A_Recons_Registrations” in Data tables.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-october-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-october-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of PIP appeals cleared at hearing is available quarterly and the last published data was released in December 2017.</p><p> </p><p>This data can be found in Table SSCS.3 of the quarterly bulletin published by the Ministry of Justice “Tribunals and gender recognition certificate statistics quarterly – July to September 2017”.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2017</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-22T14:27:36.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823503/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823503/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of personal independence claims were (a) rejected, (b) appealed and (c) went to tribunal in each of the last six months.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","122974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823504","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-23","<p>In the event that the South Fylde line did upgrade the existing single-track line infrastructure or the Train Operating Company were able to otherwise realise greater capacity on the network through other means it would be a commercial decision for the Train Operating Company to make. The current terms of our franchise agreement do not require or financially support the Train Operating Company’s operation of an additional level of frequency beyond the current levels.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-23T12:38:23.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823504/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823504/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Railways: Fylde","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 21 December 2017 to Question 120042, for what reasons the Answer of 11 December 2017 to Question 117958 stated that the decision to increase service frequency would be a commercial decision for the Train Operating Company to make when his Department has stated that it is not feasible for Northern Rail to increase the frequency of trains from the current hourly service on the South Fylde line without upgrading the existing single-track line infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823505","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-19","<p>Before granting a concessionary price we contact suppliers to ascertain that the product was not available at or below the reimbursement price listed in the Drug Tariff. While a specific assessment was not made as to why this particular product was not available at or below the reimbursement price listed in the Drug Tariff, we are aware of a number of reasons for the pressure in the supply chain generally.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-19T14:15:03.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823505/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823505/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Prescription Drugs: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 18 December 2017 to Question 119906, what steps he took to ascertain why the market price of amlodipine 5mg tablets was above the reimbursement price listed in the Drug Tariff prior to granting a concessionary price.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823506","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-23","<p>Many countries in the world regulate retail energy prices, but unlike Great Britain their markets were not previously liberalised. The Government is clear that the price cap should be temporary and that, in setting the cap, Ofgem must regard must be given to, among other things, the need to protect consumers and ensure that efficient suppliers can finance their activities.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-23T13:49:33.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823506/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823506/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department made an assessment of the operation of energy price caps in other countries prior to publishing the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823507","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-19","<p>As set out in the Impact Assessment for the draft Bill, the costs and benefits will depend on the detailed methodology the independent regulator Ofgem adopts to set the level of a tariff cap. The Government does not wish to prejudice the deliberations of Ofgem’s work in establishing the methodology, and has therefore not included quantified analysis of the costs and benefits in the Impact Assessment, but has included a qualitative discussion.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-19T14:45:51.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823507/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823507/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons the impact assessment for the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill does not include quantitative data on the effect of a price cap on (a) investment in the energy sector and (b) customers.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823508","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-22","<p>As set out in the Impact Assessment for the draft Bill, the costs and benefits will depend on the detailed methodology the independent regulator Ofgem adopts to set the level of a tariff cap. The Government does not wish to pre-judge Ofgem’s work in establishing the methodology by including quantified analysis of the costs and benefits in the Impact Assessment.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-22T13:22:00.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823508/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823508/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to make available quantitative data on the effect of a price cap on (a) investment in the energy sector and (b) customers before the Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill is introduced into Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823509","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-19","<p>The draft Bill would place a new duty on Ofgem to implement a cap on standard variable and default tariffs, so it does not remove an existing right of appeal.</p><p> </p><p>Energy companies would be able to challenge Ofgem’s decision on the setting of the cap by way of judicial review, and the Government believes that a Court is capable of considering these matters.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-19T14:43:45.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823509/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823509/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill proposes to remove the right of energy companies to appeal to the Competition and Markets Authority.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823510","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-24","<p>The draft Bill would place a new duty on Ofgem to implement a cap on standard variable and default tariffs, and provides a bespoke power for Ofgem to implement the price cap through an amendment to the licence conditions. Energy companies would be able to appeal an Ofgem decision on whether to proceed with the licence modification by way of judicial review. It does not remove an existing right of appeal.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-24T16:17:15.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823510/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823510/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of removing the right for energy companies to appeal to the Competition and Markets Authority under the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill on the ability of energy suppliers to (a) formulate business plans and (b) invest in the UK energy market.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823512","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-24","<p>The decision to implement a price cap will be made by Parliament approving a Government Bill on a matter that was a manifesto commitment. It is right for Government to decide whether the price cap would remain in place, after a report and recommendation from Ofgem.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-24T16:10:48.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823512/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823512/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill proposes to vest in him rather than Ofgem the power to remove the energy price cap in 2020 or to allow it to be extended.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823513","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-19","<p>The review in 2020, and in 2021 and 2022 if the cap remains in place, will inform Ofgem’s report on whether the conditions for effective competition are in place, and Ofgem’s recommendation. This will inform the Secretary of State’s decision on whether the cap should remain in force.</p><p> </p><p>It would not be practicable to keep the need for the price cap under constant review, however, in designing the method for setting the level of the price cap we would expect that Ofgem would need to consider how to take account of relevant short-term changes in the market.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-19T14:45:10.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823513/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823513/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill proposes to require Ofgem to review the energy price cap once a year from 2020 rather than keeping the price cap under constant review.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823514","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-19","<p>Ofgem would set the level of the price cap in a way such that, amongst other things, it would maintain incentives for switching and enable effective competition. The price cap would be lifted once the conditions for effective competition are in place in accordance with the process in clause 6.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-19T14:44:28.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823514/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823514/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823514/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the proposed provisions of the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill would permit him to remove the energy price cap in the event that such a removal would have a deleterious effect on (a) competition in the energy market and (b) energy customers.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","122984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823515","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-19","<p>Our aim is to replicate as far as possible the effects of existing trade arrangements with other countries after the UK leaves the EU. We are engaging with our trading partners to agree how best to achieve this continuity, including in relation to any implementation.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-01-19T15:05:25.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823515/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823515/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-16","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether it is his Department's policy that provisions on trade in services in any existing EU free trade agreements that are transitioned after the UK leaves the EU will be governed by EU regulations.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","122985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823516","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Government is discussing how best to secure continuity of the effects of existing EU trade agreements with partner countries, and is looking at each agreement on a case by case basis.</p><p>This work will take into account the terms and timing of any implementation period agreed with the EU, so that we can provide certainty, continuity and stability in our trade and investment relationships for businesses and consumers.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-01-19T10:37:18.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823516/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823516/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823516/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-16","EU Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of whether the adoption of existing EU Free Trade Agreements with third party countries can only happen with the agreement of the EU and those countries.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","122986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823517","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-19","<p>The current public procurement rules will continue to apply until the UK has left the EU following the successful conclusion of exit negotiations. The longer-term opportunities for our procurement regulations are being considered carefully.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-01-19T13:33:36.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823517/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823517/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Agreement on Government Procurement, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of existing devolution arrangements for procurement after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","122987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823518","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>Comparisons of uptake of medicines between different countries with different health systems are difficult and should be treated with caution. However, we are committed to working with industry on this issue and share the ambition to maximise the appropriate use of innovation in our system and tackle unwarranted variation in uptake. The Government and industry are currently working together through a series of workshops that will provide the foundation for the next medicines pricing scheme, and discussions around uptake, adoption and metrics have been a feature of those early meetings.</p><p> </p><p>The recent Government and partner bodies response to the Accelerated Access Review sets out how we will work with industry and the health system to create a streamlined and sophisticated approvals system so that cost-effective breakthrough products – be they drugs, devices, digital or diagnostics – can get into the National Health Service as fast as possible.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-24T11:57:48.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823518/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823518/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps are being taken to ensure that the UK enters the top quartile of comparator countries for the speed of adoption and overall uptake of innovative treatments as recommended in the Life Sciences Industrial Strategy.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","122988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823520","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The National Health Service will be a key partner in the delivery of the Life Sciences Industrial Strategy (LSIS) and Sector Deal. We are working with sector representatives to establish a Life Sciences Council which will oversee the LSIS and future phases of the Deal. Chaired by the Secretaries of State, the Council will include NHS England, and sector representatives. An Implementation Board, responsible for delivery of the first Sector Deal, will report to this Council, reviewing progress against objectives at quarterly meetings. Similarly, we expect to see governance bringing together broad representation from across the health sector, including the Government and NHS England.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-24T12:27:06.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823520/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823520/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the formal role of NHS England will be in delivering an effective Life Sciences Industrial Strategy and Sector Deal.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","122989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823521","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Government is currently developing its approach to the mandate to NHS England for 2018-19, in light of the extra £2.8 billion to 2019/20 provided through the Autumn Budget to support the National Health Service. Both NHS England and Healthwatch England are involved in its development as statutory consultees.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-24T12:28:32.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823521/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823521/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what measures will be included within NHS England’s mandate for 2018-19 to formalise its role in implementing the Life Sciences Industrial Strategy.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","122990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823522","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is committed to playing its part in delivering the vision set out in the Life Sciences Industrial Strategy. Ensuring that appraisals are fit for purpose in a fast-changing sector is critical. NICE has recently taken steps to do this by introducing changes to its processes to support faster access to the most effective treatments, while addressing affordability issues. In addition, NICE has recently consulted on further changes to streamline its technology appraisal processes so that it is better able to develop new guidance on innovative drugs and medical technologies.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in the response to the Accelerated Access Review, we are also introducing a new Accelerated Access Pathway, to streamline regulatory and market access decisions for a small number of products, getting breakthrough products that we believe will be truly transformative to patients even more quickly.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-24T16:38:26.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823522/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823522/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps are being taken to update and evolve value assessments of drugs, medical devices and diagnostics, as recommended in the Life Sciences Industrial Strategy.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","122991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823523","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department wants patients with cystic fibrosis to benefit from clinically and cost effective treatments, and we welcome the on-going dialogue between Vertex and NHS England to pursue a deal that would make Orkambi available to National Health Service patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-24T12:13:27.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823523/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823523/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Orkambi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the extension of Orkambi's licence to treat patients aged six and over, what support his Department is giving to further negotiations among NICE, NHS England and the drug manufacturer, Vertex, on access to that medicine for people with cystic fibrosis.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","122992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823524","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-19","<p>The nature of Carillion business means that it sub-contracts significant proportions of its work, with the potential for those sub-contractors to sub-contract out further elements.</p><p>At this stage in the liquidation process it is too soon for the Liquidator to have gathered in full details of the company’s debts and creditors. The Liquidation process for such a complex and interconnected group of companies will take some time. The Official receiver and his Special Managers have access to the records of the company and will be analysing these over the coming days.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-19T14:47:48.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823524/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823524/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Carillion: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of (a) the amount of money owed by Carillion to and (b) the number of self-employed sub-contactor creditors of Carillion for (i) public sector and (ii) private sector contracts.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","122993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823525","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Department has no plans to undertake an assessment of the potential merits of issuing maternity exemption certificates to people taking adoption leave. Almost 90% of prescription items are free on the National Health Service in England and for those who do not qualify for an exemption, prescription prepayment certificates are available. A holder of a 12 month certificate can get all the prescriptions they need for just £2 per week.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-19T14:16:04.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823525/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823525/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 16 January 2018 to Question 122208, if he will make it his policy to conduct an assessment of the potential merits of issuing maternity exemption certificates to people taking adoption leave.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","122994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823526","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-22","<p>The number of Regular and Reserve Army applications received between 1 January – 31 October 2017 was around [1]113,500.</p><p> </p><p>Of those, as at 31 October 2017, around 3,100 had begun Phase 1 training. In addition, around 17,400 are still in the application process or have deferred their application.</p><p> </p><p>The Defence Recruiting System will enable a quicker and easier recruitment process for applicants and the Armed Forces. It is too early to judge the impact on applications of the transfer to the new system.</p><p> </p><p>[1] All figures are single service estimates.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-01-22T16:11:00.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823526/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823526/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-16","Army: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to his Oral Answer to the hon. Member for Llanelli of 15 January 2018, how many Army applications were (a) received and (b) successful in 2017; and how many applicants (i) were affected by or (ii) had their applications lost as a result of errors on the new online application system.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","122995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823527","Department for Education","false","2018-01-24","<p>The introduction of the national funding formula in 2018-19 will allocate funding on the basis of the specific characteristics of every school and pupil.</p><p>Allocations for 2018-19 for each local authority were confirmed on 19 December 2017 and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019</a>. The allocations take into account the latest pupil numbers from the October 2017 census. For Cornwall, the national funding formula means an increase in schools funding of 1.7% per pupil in 2018-19 and 2.7% in 2019-20.</p><p>Local authorities will continue to set their own local formulae which will determine individual schools’ budgets in their areas, in 2018-19 and 2019-20, in consultation with local schools.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-01-24T17:12:20.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823527/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823527/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-16","Schools: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the overall increase in funding for Cornwall’s schools as a result of the implementation of the fair funding formula.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","122996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823528","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-12","<p>Each Department is individually responsible for overseeing levels of preparedness and the potential consequences of civil emergency risks for those sectors within their purview.</p><p> </p><p>Within the Cabinet Office, the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office has oversight of all of the Cabinet Office’s activities. The Minister for Implementation has responsibility for civil contingencies policy.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-12T14:09:00.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823528/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823528/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Emergencies: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Minister has responsibility for civil contingencies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","122997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823530","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>The government’s independent expert panel has considered cladding material other than aluminium composite material (ACM) and their advice on external wall systems that do not incorporate ACM was published on 11 December 2017. This advice is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/advice-for-building-owners-external-wall-systems-that-do-not-incorporate-acm" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/advice-for-building-owners-external-wall-systems-that-do-not-incorporate-acm</a>.</p><p>The expert panel has also advised on safety considerations arising from wind-loading of external wall insulation systems incorporating render or brick-slip finishes. This advice was published on 11 December 2017 and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/advice-for-building-owners-external-wall-insulation-ewi-systems-with-a-render-or-brick-slip-finish" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/advice-for-building-owners-external-wall-insulation-ewi-systems-with-a-render-or-brick-slip-finish</a>.</p><p>Government is commissioning further research to support further understanding in the industry of the fire performance of external wall systems. This will be developed with a view to publication in summer 2018.</p><p>Finally, to help building owners and industry to understand what other cladding systems may be safe on high-rise buildings, the Building Research Establishment has published a list of historical data on cladding systems which have passed a large-scale BS8414 test.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-23T13:19:58.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823530/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823530/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the fire safety of high-rise cladding material other than aluminium composite material following the failure of such cladding on the Barley Mow Estate in Tower Hamlets.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","122998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823531","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-19","<p>I refer the honourable member to my Written Statement (HCWS401), made on 15 January which contains the number of parents with a Tax-Free Childcare account.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-01-19T12:53:26.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823531/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823531/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many parents have accessed tax-free child care since April 2017.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","122999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823532","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-24","<p>The latest revenue forecast for the Soft Drinks Industry Levy can be found in ‘Table 2.2’ of the Budget Document, published alongside Autumn Budget 2017. This forecast already accounts for a behavioural response whereby producers lower the sugar content of their drinks, promote lower sugar alternatives and reduce portion sizes.</p><p>Table 2.2. can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661380/B2017Table2.2.XLSX" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661380/B2017Table2.2.XLSX</a></p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-24T17:27:25.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823532/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823532/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-16","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the decision by soft drinks suppliers to repackage the size of their bottles and cans on the revenue to the Exchequer from the soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","123000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823533","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>The information requested is published in the Annual NOMS Digest 2016/17, available at.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017 </a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Select <em>Supplementary Tables and MDT Data Tool &gt; 07 Random Mandatory Drug Testing &gt; Table 7.1</em></p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T18:46:39.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823533/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823533/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-16","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the rate of positive tests from mandatory drug testing in prisons in England and Wales was in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","123001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823534","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Private Finance Initiative (PFI) contract between the Royal Liverpool and Broadgreen University Hospitals NHS Trust and the PFI Project Company – The Hospital Company (Liverpool) Holdings Ltd - is still in place, which means that the Company is still contractually obliged to manage the project and source a construction firm or subcontractor who can continue the building work. This is important for the Trust and also an incentive for Liverpool Hospital Company to minimise delay. Additionally, the Department and NHS Improvement have been supporting the Trust with contingency planning for this to ensure there is minimal disruption.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-19T11:52:35.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823534/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823534/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will make an assessment of the effect of Carillion plc's collapse on the Liverpool Hospital Company; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","123002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823535","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-19","<p>​Her Majesty's Government consistently promotes and defends the right to freedom of religion or belief (FoRB) in a variety of ways, including at the United Nations. For example, we work to sustain UN Human Rights Council consensus on the adoption and implementation of the European Union sponsored Resolution on 'Freedom of Religion or Belief' and the Organisation for Islamic Cooperation sponsored Resolution on 'Combating Religious Intolerance'. Furthermore, the FCO minister with direct responsibility for human rights, Lord Ahmad, stressed the importance of working to defend the right to freedom of religion or belief (FoRB) when he addressed the United Nations Human Rights Council (HRC) in September, 2017.</p><p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office ministers and officials routinely raise individual cases and highlight practices and laws that discriminate against people on the basis of their religion or belief. We also continue to support a number of projects to promote tolerance through the FCO's Magna Carta Fund, including a project to promote the teaching of religious tolerance in more than 50 secondary schools in Iraq, Lebanon, and Morocco.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-19T14:53:44.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823535/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823535/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","Middle East: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations at the UN on the increase in persecution of Christians and other non-Muslim religions in the Middle East and steps to prevent such persecution.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","123003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823536","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-19","<p>Further to previous answers I have given on this topic, HMRC currently believes that roughly 5-6% of RTI returns are late, and about 1% are missing. HMRC does not currently have an estimate for how many are incorrect. HMRC set up the Late, Missing and Incorrect initiative jointly with DWP on 1 November 2017 to investigate all these areas and find ways of improving them.</p><p> </p><p>The work of the Late, Missing and Incorrect initiative will be monitored and HMRC expects to see a reduction in the proportions over time.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","123005","2018-01-19T12:49:51.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823536/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823536/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-16","PAYE: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 January 2018 to Question 90331, what estimate he has made of how many RTI returns are (a) late, (b) missing, and (c) incorrect.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","123004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823537","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-19","<p>Further to previous answers I have given on this topic, HMRC currently believes that roughly 5-6% of RTI returns are late, and about 1% are missing. HMRC does not currently have an estimate for how many are incorrect. HMRC set up the Late, Missing and Incorrect initiative jointly with DWP on 1 November 2017 to investigate all these areas and find ways of improving them.</p><p> </p><p>The work of the Late, Missing and Incorrect initiative will be monitored and HMRC expects to see a reduction in the proportions over time.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","123004","2018-01-19T12:49:51.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823537/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823537/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-16","PAYE: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 January to Question 90331, that the Late, Missing and Incorrect joint initiative between his Department and Department for Work and Pensions on PAYE Real Time Information believes that around 5% or 6% of RTI returns are late, missing or incorrect, by when he expects to reduce those proportions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","123005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823538","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p><strong> </strong>The Home Office does not hold this information.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick  Hurd",,"2018-01-22T18:00:59.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823538/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823538/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Police: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was spent from the public purse on (a) hire and (b) police cars by each constabulary in the North West in 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823540","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence will be marking this year's Holocaust Memorial Day in the Department's London Headquarters Memorial Courtyard on Wednesday 24 January. The event is part of a cross-Government commemoration involving 18 Departments and has been organised in conjunction with the Holocaust Educational Trust. This will be an opportunity to hear the personal testimony of a Holocaust survivor and consider Defence's contribution to the liberation of the concentration camps. It will also be a chance to reflect on the enduring relevance of the Holocaust to today's world.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-01-24T16:01:30.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823540/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823540/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-16","World War II: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if his Department will take steps to commemorate (a) Holocaust Memorial Day 2018, (b) the liberation of Auschwitz-Birkenau by allied forces and (c) the role played by British forces in defeating the Nazi regime; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","123007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823541","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-24","<p>The brave British and Canadian liberation of Bergen-Belsen on 15 April 1945 marked the end of suffering for thousands of men, women and children. Whilst the Ministry of Defence has no plans to hold a dedicated commemorative event, the Department will support events where possible.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-01-24T16:02:51.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823541/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823541/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-16","World War II: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will take steps to commemorate the role of British soldiers in liberating Bergen-Belson in World War Two.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","123008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823542","Home Office","false","2018-01-19","<p>This information is not collected centrally by the Home Office.</p><p>How forces deploy resources and equip police vehicles is an operational matter for chief constables.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick  Hurd",,"2018-01-19T12:43:03.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823542/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823542/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Police: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was spent by (a) Lancashire Constabulary and (b) Greater Manchester Constabulary in (i) 2015, (ii) 2016 and (iii) 2017 on painting rainbow flags and providing other LGBT friendly facilities for police cars.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823543","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department funds the Holocaust Memorial Day Trust which provides resources to local authorities to support local Holocaust Memorial Day events. In 2017 there were 7,700 local Holocaust Memorial Day events across the country many of them were hosted by local authorities. We are expecting the same this year but will not have the total numbers until after Holocaust Memorial Day.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-24T14:16:31.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823543/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823543/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Holocaust Memorial Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if his Department will support local authorities to hold memorial events for Holocaust Memorial Day 2018.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","123010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823544","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-23","<p>We continue to challenge the rail industry to develop proposals for pricing and delivering more flexible ticketing options for those who work or commute part-time. Progress has been made on delivery of more flexible tickets. c2c have a Flexi-Season on a smart card. Arriva Trains Wales have introduced a Mobile Multi-Flex product for customers in Cardiff and the surrounding areas. In addition both the recently announced South Western and West Midlands franchises include the announcement of a new flexible season ticket which will benefit people working fewer than 5 days a week.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-23T12:40:52.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823544/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823544/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish an assessment of the non-provision by (a) Govia Thameslink Railway and (b) other franchisees of part-time season tickets on (i) women returning to work after having children and (ii) other people needing to work part-time; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","123011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823545","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Task and Finish group on Taxi and Private Hire Vehicles was established by the then Minister of State for Transport, John Hayes, and was in regular contact with the Chair to discuss the progress of the group. I intend to meet with the Chair shortly and look forward to receiving the group’s findings soon.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-24T13:59:34.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823545/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823545/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when minsters of his Department last met with members of the Department's working group on taxis and private hire licensing, and what the outcomes of those meetings were.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","123012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823546","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department hosted in partnership with the Holocaust Educational Trust and the Holocaust Memorial Day Trust, a Holocaust Memorial Day event on Wednesday 17 January for staff. We were honoured to hear the testimony of Holocaust survivor Janine Webber and two Holocaust Educational Trust Ambassadors Jack Pepper from the Glyn School and Chloe Smith from Furze Platt Senior School.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-24T14:14:11.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823546/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823546/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Holocaust Memorial Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has plans to commemorate Holocaust Memorial Day 2018.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","123013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823547","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Task and Finish group on Taxi and Private Hire Vehicles was established by the then Minister of State for Transport, John Hayes, and has received submissions from a number of disability representation organisations. I look forward to receiving the group’s findings soon.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-24T14:02:29.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823547/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823547/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to ensure people with disabilities are represented on his Department's taxi and private hire working group; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","123014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823548","Home Office","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Home office does not hold any information centrally on the number of police horses deployed in each constabulary.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick  Hurd",,"2018-01-19T12:43:29.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823548/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823548/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Lancashire Constabulary: Horses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions horses from the Lancashire Constabulary were used for activities outside constabulary's area in 2017; what the date, venue and nature of those activities was on each such occasion; and what the cost of each such deployment was.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823549","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-24","<p>We work closely with the Community Security Trust, the Police and the Home Office to tackle antisemitic incidents, which have no place in our communities.</p><p>The Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government hosts the Antisemitism Working Group which brings together community representatives and officials from across Government to ensure a coordinated response to antisemitism, whether at home, abroad or online.</p><p>The UK was also the first country in the world to adopt the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance's working definition of Antisemitism which is a useful tool in understanding how Antisemitism manifests itself in the 21st century.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-24T16:33:36.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823549/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823549/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment his Department has made of the level of antisemitism and Holocaust denial; and what steps his Department is taking to tackle antisemitism and Holocaust denial.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","123016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823550","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Department only holds data on PIP awards changed and unchanged at appeal. Therefore the awards changed may include a very small number of appeals where the award may have reduced.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The table below shows the number of appeals against awards of Personal Independent Payment where the award was changed and unchanged at appeal for St Helens South and Whiston for the last three years.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year of appeal outcome</p></td><td><p>Award changed at appeal</p></td><td><p>Award unchanged at appeal</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>90</p></td><td><p>60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr'17 to Oct'17</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Latest available data to October 2017</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The information for Employment Support Allowance (ESA) is not readily available and can only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-19T10:47:50.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823550/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823550/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Social Security Benefits: St Helens South and Whiston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many appeals for (a) ESA and (b) PIP in St Helens South and Whiston constituency resulted in an increase in the amount awarded in each of the last three years; and what the average value of each such increase was per week.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","123017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823552","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-23","<p>We expect the new diesel rolling stock which is starting to come on stream, being required to meet the latest emissions standards, will help reduce air pollution by replacing the oldest diesel trains built decades ago. However, the Government is committed to further improving air quality and is taking action across a range of transport modes. With respect to rail, in September 2017, the Rail Safety and Standards Board (RSSB) commissioned a study of air quality in Kings Cross, Euston and Edinburgh Waverley stations. The study will start in early 2018 and is expected to be completed in 2019. In addition, Network Rail, in partnership with the University of Birmingham, are undertaking air quality monitoring at Birmingham New Street Station. This work is expected to be completed shortly.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-23T14:49:38.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823552/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823552/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-16","Railways: Diesel Fuel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of diesel trains on air quality at railway stations.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","123018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823553","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-19","<p>Our media should reflect the population as a whole. The government believes that broadcasters should be leading the way on improving diversity monitoring in support of this goal, including by voluntarily providing data across all of the equality strands to Ofcom. It is right that voluntary approaches are fully explored before legislative change is considered, and the government urges all parties to work together to improve monitoring of diversity levels. Government will continue to work closely with Ofcom on this matter.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-19T09:55:03.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823553/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823553/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-16","Telecommunications: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the letter sent to her by the chair of Ofcom regarding the Communications Acts 2003, 27(6), if she will make it her policy to extend the Communications Acts 2003, 27(6), to include all equality strands covered in the Equality Act 2010, specifically religion or belief.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","123019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823554","Home Office","false","2018-01-19","<p>The Government welcomes the contribution that international students make to the UK economy. We recognise that international students enhance our educational institutions both financially and culturally; enrich the experience of domestic students; and become important ambassadors for the United Kingdom in later life. The Government has recently commissioned the Migration Advisory Committee to undertake a study into the costs and benefits of international students</p><p>There is no limit on the number of international students who can come to the UK and there are no plans to change this. So long as students are compliant with immigration rules they should make a very limited contribution to net migration numbers</p><p>The independent Office for National Statistics is responsible for the production of the net migration statistics. In line with the internationally agreed UN definition, these statistics define a migrant as someone changing their normal place of residence for more than a year. Students are therefore included in the same way as other migrants.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline  Nokes","123055","2018-01-19T12:44:46.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823554/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823554/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has undertaken a societal or cultural cost-benefit analysis on removing non-EU students from their Government's net migration target.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","123020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823555","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-22","<p>Companies House carries out systematic checks on all information received, ensuring that it is valid, complete and in compliance with company law filing requirements. This includes people with significant control (PSC) information provided on incorporation and throughout the life of a company.</p><p> </p><p>Companies House is committed to ensuring companies comply with the requirements of the PSC regime, our current compliance rate is 98%. There are 20 staff employed to deal with PSC compliance activities and 18 of these have been recruited in the last year. They will recruit further staff this year.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-22T15:11:56.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823555/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823555/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-16","Companies House: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 10 January 2018 to Question 121070, how many staff at Companies House monitor the accuracy of data on the beneficial ownership register for companies; and how many of those staff have been recruited in the past 12 months.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","123021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823556","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>Claimants to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) receive a decision letter once their claim has been determined by a Departmental Case Manager. The decision letter sets out all the assessment activities, the relevant functional descriptor applicable to the individual for each activity and the points each descriptor carries. Where a claimant asks for a mandatory reconsideration they will receive a further decision letter which again sets out the assessment activities, the relevant functional descriptor applicable to the individual for each activity and the points each descriptor carries. The assessment activities and descriptors used in PIP can be found in part 2 of the PIP Assessment Guide available on www.gov.uk: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/665635/pip-assessment-guide-part-2-assessment-criteria.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/665635/pip-assessment-guide-part-2-assessment-criteria.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Claimants to Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) receive a decision letter once their claim has been determined by a Departmental Decision Maker. An entitlement decision letter sets out what the claimant needs to do next and which group the claimant has been placed in and a disallowance decision letter sets out the functional activities laid down in legislation and the justification for the number of points awarded. Following a Mandatory Reconsideration a new decision letter will be issued confirming either entitlement or disallowance; however no additional information is provided on the functional activities. The assessment activities and descriptors used in the Work Capability Assessment for ESA can be found in the ‘Employment and Support Allowance: the Work Capability Assessment: Detailed Guide’ and the ‘Work Capability Assessment Handbook’ both available on www.gov.uk: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/esa214-a-guide-to-employment-and-support-allowance-the-work-capability-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/esa214-a-guide-to-employment-and-support-allowance-the-work-capability-assessment</a> and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-handbook-for-healthcare-professionals" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-handbook-for-healthcare-professionals</a>.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-24T17:34:46.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823556/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823556/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what arrangements the Government has in place to inform claimants of the assessment criteria against which they are measured when they apply for a PIP or ESA reconsideration or appeal.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","123022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823557","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-22","<p>Where our customers advise us that they need assistance to access our services and information, we make reasonable adjustments to meet their individual needs. This means the Department communicates with customers in a variety of different formats such as Braille, audio, large print, through third party interpreters or by arranging for a member of staff to visit the customer in their home.</p><p> </p><p>Forms are available as a reasonable adjustment in electronic formats compatible with assistive software such as JAWS, Dragon, NVDA, Read &amp; Write, and Zoomtext.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is continuously working to improve its written customer communications products, including letters, forms and leaflets, so they are clear and accessible to as many of our customers as possible. We follow accessible design principles, including the use of plain language.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-22T15:28:22.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823557/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823557/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Social Security Benefits: Forms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department has taken to ensure that benefit assessment and claim forms are offered in accessible formats.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","123023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823558","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Government response to the consultation on ‘ <em>Tackling unfair practices in the leasehold market</em>’ set out a range of measures to cut out unfair and abusive practices within the leasehold system. This included introducing legislation to prohibit the development of new build leasehold houses, other than in exceptional circumstances, and restricting ground rents in newly established leases of houses and flats to a peppercorn (zero financial value).</p><p>For existing leaseholders, the Government wants to see developer compensation schemes going further and faster, with support extended to all those with onerous ground rents, including second hand buyers and for customers to be proactively contacted. We will be keeping a close eye on progress and will consider measures that could be pursued to take action if necessary.</p><p>We want to make it easier for existing leaseholders to exercise their right to buy their freehold, or extend their lease, for this to be faster, fairer and cheaper, and to be available as soon as possible.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-01-23T13:21:10.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823558/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823558/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Leasehold: Ground Rent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the ministerial statement HCWS384 of 21 December 2017, what steps he plans to take to prevent onerous ground rents in already existing leasehold properties.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","123024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823559","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Social Security Benefits Up-rating Regulations restrict for overseas residents the annual increases in certain benefits, including state pensions. This continues the long-standing policy of not up-rating the state pension in payment to people who are overseas residents, except where there is a legal requirement to up-rate for example the European Union Co-ordination Regulations and Reciprocal Agreements that allow for up-rating.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-01-23T17:04:37.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823559/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823559/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2017 to Question 108399, whether there are any factors legally preventing her from granting up-rated state pensions to all overseas UK pensioners regardless of whether the UK has a reciprocal agreement with their country of residence.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","123025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823560","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>The government is committed to a long-term sustainable funding model for supported housing as set out in the policy statement published on 31 October.</p><p>We are consulting on this model. The consultation closes on 23 January 2018.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-23T13:26:33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823560/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823560/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Supported Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's funding for supported housing policy paper, published in October 2017, what policies the Government is putting in place to ensure funding for non-statutory supported housing is sustained in the long-term.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","123026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823561","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>This department does not collect data on deaths of people sleeping rough. No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why Government has committed to halving rough sleeping by 2022 and eliminating it altogether by 2027. We have announced a new Rough Sleeping and Homelessness Reduction Taskforce, chaired by the Secretary of State, which will drive forward the implementation of a cross-Government strategy to tackle this issue.</p><p>We have allocated over £1 billion through to 2020 to prevent and reduce all forms of homelessness including piloting a Housing First approach for some of the most entrenched rough sleepers.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-23T13:36:29.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823561/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823561/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-16","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the answer of 27 December 2017 to Question 120298, what information his Department holds on the number of people that have died while sleeping rough in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","123027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823563","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-22","<p>The UK is the leading donor in education services to the people of South Sudan. Through the Girls’ Education South Sudan Programme, the UK supports over 3,500 schools to deliver basic education, including literacy, and is helping to keep up to a quarter of a million girls in class. Ensuring the continuity of education for the children of South Sudan will build the essential foundations for future peace and ensure that education is not lost to an entire generation.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-22T18:07:23.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823563/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823563/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-16","South Sudan: Literacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to increase literacy in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823564","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-22","<p>The recent Green Paper, ‘Transforming Children and Young People’s Mental Health Provision’, includes a proposal to trial a four week waiting time for access to specialist National Health Service children and young people’s mental health services. New Mental Health Support Teams, a further announcement in the green paper, will also enable children and young people to access earlier help for emerging problems. Both approaches will be tested using trailblazer areas, operational from 2019, to understand what works.</p><p> </p><p>Two waiting time standards applicable to children and young people’s mental health are already in place; the early intervention in psychosis standard is currently exceeding its target and the children’s eating disorder standard is on track to meet its target by 2020/21.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-22T11:32:44.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823564/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823564/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the Education Policy Institute’s report Access and Waiting Times in Children and Young People’s Mental Health Services, what steps he plans to take to reduce the variation in waiting times for mental health treatment across the country.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","123029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823565","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>The available information on the number of Universal Credit claimants that have managed payments made directly to their landlord, is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-01-24T10:46:06.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823565/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823565/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Universal Credit: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants have managed payments made directly to their landlord.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","123030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823566","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>We are acutely aware that during armed conflict, civilians often pay a heavy price. It is essential that all parties to the conflict in Yemen, including Houthi forces, comply with International Humanitarian Law (IHL). We regularly raise the importance of IHL compliance with the Saudi-led Coalition, and when allegations of IHL are made, we insist that they are investigated and that any lessons are acted upon. We have also provided training to support the ability of the Saudi-led Coalition to comply with IHL.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-24T16:21:00.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823566/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823566/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterpart in Saudi Arabia on the effect of Saudi Arabia's airstrikes in Yemen on the civilian population.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","123031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823567","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-01-24T10:46:26.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823567/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823567/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Universal Credit: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information her Department holds on the number of managed payments of the housing costs element of universal credit which have been made to the wrong landlord, council or housing association in the last twelve months.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","123032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823568","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>I refer the Hon. Gentleman to the answers of 8 January 2018 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-21/121059/" target="_blank">121059</a> and 21 December <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-18/119929/" target="_blank">119929</a>.</p><p>Our design priorities are constantly being evaluated and updated. This means the Department has not yet set a date for implementation of the automated system.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","123034 ; 123035","2018-01-24T10:46:56.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823568/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823568/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 January 2019 to Question 121059, on universal credit, what data and research the Government would require before it would judge an automated system to be approved.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823569","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>I refer the Hon. Gentleman to the answers of 8 January 2018 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-21/121059/" target="_blank">121059</a> and 21 December <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-18/119929/" target="_blank">119929</a>.</p><p>Our design priorities are constantly being evaluated and updated. This means the Department has not yet set a date for implementation of the automated system.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","123033 ; 123035","2018-01-24T10:46:56.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823569/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823569/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 January 2018 to Question 121059, whether the Government is conducting data collection and research on the use of an automated system for universal credit claimants.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823571","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>I refer the Hon. Gentleman to the answers of 8 January 2018 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-21/121059/" target="_blank">121059</a> and 21 December <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-12-18/119929/" target="_blank">119929</a>.</p><p>Our design priorities are constantly being evaluated and updated. This means the Department has not yet set a date for implementation of the automated system.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","123033 ; 123034","2018-01-24T10:46:56.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823571/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823571/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is her policy to implement an automated system for universal credit claimants to reset their login details; and what the timetable is for setting up such a system.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823572","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-22","<p>The UK is a leading contributor to the health sector in South Sudan, helping to deliver almost 8 million patient consultations last year. The UK is the lead donor to the Health Pooled Fund (HPF), through which we are supporting over 1,000 frontline health centres across South Sudan to improve access to quality health services, including preventing the spread of disease through routine immunisations for children. Last year, the HPF provided almost 5.4 million health consultations to children under 5. Other public health measures include UK funding for the Integrated Community Case Management programme to better identify and treat the main causes of child mortality in local communities.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-22T18:08:38.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823572/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823572/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-16","South Sudan: Public Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to assist with (a) disease reduction and (b) other public health measures in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823573","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-22","<p>The department does not hold data on the number of paying parents who are acting as company directors.</p><p> </p><p>The Child Maintenance Service is currently in the process of assuring employment data and therefore this will be available at a future date when it would be released in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-01-22T15:28:39.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823573/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823573/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of the number of paying parents involved in pay arrangements though the child maintence service who are listed as self-employed or as company directors.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823574","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Commercial Models Team (CMT) assists departments and other public sector organisations to deliver better services at lower cost and devise and implement commercial models for collaborating across the public sector and between the private and public sectors.</p><p> </p><p>By way of example, they continue to work with the Department for Communities and Local Government and HM Treasury to transform the way the Local Government Pension Scheme invests its £260 billion of assets. The government has received proposals from Local Government Pension Scheme administering authorities in England and Wales to consolidate their assets into a small number of pools to take advantage of their scale. These pools are expected to deliver<strong> </strong>annual savings in investment costs of at least £200-300 million. We will also work with administering authorities to establish a new Local Government Pension Scheme infrastructure investment platform, in line with their proposals, in order to boost their capacity and capability to invest in infrastructure.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-01-22T16:18:18.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823574/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823574/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","List of Ministerial Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the List of Ministerial responsibilities, what the definition is of commercial models.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823575","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-12","<p><strong>What Works:</strong> ‘What Works’ refers to the initiative launched by the Cabinet Office and HM Treasury in 2013 to ensure that the best available evidence informs spending decisions and the delivery of public services. It brings together of a network of 10 independent What Works Centres in policy areas such education, health, local economic growth, and children’s social care. These centres synthesise the existing evidence base in their fields of expertise and produce guidance for decision-makers both in government and on the frontline. Many of these research centres also commission or conduct primary research to fill gaps in the evidence base.</p><p> </p><p>The National What Works Adviser and the Cabinet Office’s What Works Team coordinates this network. They operate across government to share findings from the centres and support civil servants in the generation and use of evidence. For more information, please see: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/what-works-network" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/what-works-network</a></p><p> </p><p><strong>Behaviour change: </strong>Behaviour change in this context refers to the use of behavioural insights to bring about change and improvements, for example in policymaking and service delivery. For more information, please see the recently launched behavioural insights framework: <a href="http://ccs-agreements.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/contracts/rm6004" target="_blank">http://ccs-agreements.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/contracts/rm6004</a></p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-12T14:10:38.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823575/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823575/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Cabinet Office: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the responsibilities of the Minister for Implementation, what the terms what works and behaviour change refer to.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823576","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>In the context of the responsibilities for the Minister for the Constitution, Knowledge Management refers to the Cabinet Office’s responsibilities for government record keeping and information management systems.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-01-25T16:25:59.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823576/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823576/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Cabinet Office: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to responsibilities of the Minister for the Constitution, what the term knowledge management refers to.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823577","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-08","<p>Cabinet Office Domestic refers to the corporate services and internal functions within Cabinet Office. This includes Cabinet Office Security, Estates, Digital and Technology, Human Resources and Finance.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-03-08T15:57:21.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823577/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823577/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Cabinet Office: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the responsibilities of the Minister for the Constitution, what the term Cabinet Office domestic refers to.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823578","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>The continuing collapse of the South Sudanese economy is exacerbating the already dire humanitarian and security situation. The World Bank expects the economy to contract by nearly 7 percent in 2017-18 due to ongoing conflict and disruption to oil production. The currency continues to depreciate and inflation remains stubbornly high at over 100 percent a year. Average household incomes have fallen by 80 percent since 2013 and 1.5 million people are on the brink of famine, more than twice as many as in January 2017. The solution to the economic and humanitarian crises is peace. The UK is playing an active role in peace talks and encourages all parties to enter the next round of the High Level Revitalisation Forum with a genuine commitment to peace.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-24T14:26:36.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823578/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823578/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","South Sudan: Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the economic situation in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823579","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>Government communications is a function within the civil service. It includes media relations, campaigns and marketing, digital communication and internal communication. Its purpose is to support the delivery of public services, the implementation of policy, to promote the UK globally and to explain government priorities and decisions.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-03-01T16:53:39.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823579/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823579/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-16","Cabinet Office: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the responsibilities of the Minister for the Constitution, what the term government communications refers to.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823580","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-24","<p>The UK is working closely with the Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD), the United States and Norway, and the wider international community, to give the High Level Revitalisation Forum the best chance of success. The UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan participated in the first round of talks and is supporting preparations for the second round of talks, scheduled to take place in February. We are calling on all parties to end violations of the Cessation of Hostilities and to enter into the next round of talks with a genuine commitment to making progress.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-24T14:29:40.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823580/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823580/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-16","South Sudan: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support he is giving to the High Level Revitalisation Forum in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","123044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823582","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-19","<p>The claiming process for Personal Independence Payment (PIP), including the arrangements to invite existing Disability Living Allowance (DLA) claimants to claim PIP, was co-produced with the assistance of disabled people, carers and their representative support organisations to ensure it works effectively. Up to the end of October 2017 nearly 1,177,000 DLA to PIP claims had been registered, of which nearly 1,100,000 claims had been cleared. To ensure continuity of payment, DLA claimants continue to get paid while their PIP claim is being assessed.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State and Ministers receive a wide range of representations about PIP from individuals, organisations and Parliamentarians. However, as PIP is a different benefit to DLA, with different assessment criteria, someone moving from DLA to PIP will not automatically be entitled to PIP, or guaranteed the same level of award. PIP is intended to focus support on those who need it most and 38 per cent of those previously in receipt of DLA are currently receiving the highest possible rate of benefit compared with only 15 per cent on DLA of working age at May 2013.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-19T11:33:36.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823582/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823582/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that the transfer from disability living allowance to personal independence payments is made effectively; and what representations she has received on claimants whose payments have changed significantly despite there being no change in their circumstances.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823583","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>The military and political activities of Hizballah are distinct, though links exist between the senior leaders of the political and military wings. The UK proscribed Hizballah's External Security Organisation in March 2001 and in 2008 the proscription was extended to Hizballah's military apparatus.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2018-01-22T15:56:42.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823583/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823583/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Hezbollah","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the nature of the links between the political and military wings of Hezbollah; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","123046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823584","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>The percentage of PIP and ESA appeals cleared at a tribunal hearing where the appeal decision was in favour of the claimant can be found in Table SSCS.3 of the quarterly bulletin “Tribunals and gender recognition certificate statistics quarterly – July to September 2017”.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>These figures include all Mandatory Reconsideration (MR) decisions subsequently appealed - not just ‘failed’ MRs where the original decision has been maintained, but also MRs where the award was changed but which were still disputed.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","123049","2018-01-24T17:33:37.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823584/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823584/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of PIP cases taken to tribunal following a failed mandatory reconsideration are successful in changing the original decision.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823585","Home Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>Hizballah's External Security Organisation was proscribed in March 2001 and in 2008 the proscription was extended to Hizballah's military apparatus including the Jihad Council. I have received representations from Parliamentarians, civil society organisations and members of the public amongst others on whether to extend the proscription of Hizballah to cover the whole organisation.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2018-01-22T15:55:59.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823585/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823585/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-16","Hezbollah","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received on proscribing Hezbollah; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","123048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823586","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-24","<p>The percentage of PIP and ESA appeals cleared at a tribunal hearing where the appeal decision was in favour of the claimant can be found in Table SSCS.3 of the quarterly bulletin “Tribunals and gender recognition certificate statistics quarterly – July to September 2017”.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>These figures include all Mandatory Reconsideration (MR) decisions subsequently appealed - not just ‘failed’ MRs where the original decision has been maintained, but also MRs where the award was changed but which were still disputed.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","123047","2018-01-24T17:33:37.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823586/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823586/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-16","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of ESA cases taken to tribunal following a failed mandatory reconsideration are successful in changing the original decision.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823587","Scotland Office","false","2018-01-25","<p>The UK Government has instructed the Official Receiver to maintain public services across the UK. Those public services which are provided in Scotland by Carillion through contracts with devolved bodies are for the relevant devolved bodies to oversee. The UK and Scottish Governments are in close contact at all levels, and are working together constructively.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-01-25T12:49:13.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823587/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823587/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-01-16","Carillion: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what steps he is taking to ensure that major public sector construction projects in Scotland held by Carillion will still proceed as planned.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","123050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823588","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Department has made no such estimate. FP10 prescriptions forms do not specify what clinical indication the medicine/device is being prescribed for, therefore the requested data is not collected.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-24T12:15:06.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823588/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823588/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-16","Asthma: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will make an estimate of the average yearly cost to patients of paying for prescribed asthma medication.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","123051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823589","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-24","<p>Running costs for individual barracks are not held in the format requested as contracts are let by region.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","123053 ; 123054","2018-01-24T16:12:00.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823589/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/823589/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-16","Elizabeth Barracks: Operating Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate has been made of the running costs to the public purse of the Elizabeth Barracks in Pirbright, Woking, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","123052"
